segments.text: 19 and 30, no 19 and 20, I believe, my father became a member of the Texas A&M University staff.
And what was his position in the university?
He was first a county agent in the extension service and before he retired he became director of the extension service.
Okay, and where had you lived previously before, or where had they lived previously before they came here?
In northeast Texas.
In northeast Texas.
I see.
Okay.
Could you give me your earliest recollections of the community, in other words, here in Bryan, what it looked like, how it was, you know, the landscape and the buildings and so on?
Well, it was a very pleasant, small town where...
Everybody knew everybody else, where everybody knew where everybody lives.
Nobody ever paid attention to the names of the streets, they just said so and so lives three blocks on the other side of such and such a place.

We had Allen Academy, it was called then, it's now called Allen School, and everybody was interested in the welfare of the boys there, and the students at A&M University, which was called A&M College at that time.
Could you tell me a little bit about how large the community was at the time?
Between 5,000 and 6,000 people.
Could you tell me a little bit about your school years, where you went to school and what the schooling was like then as compared to today?
You mean a school here in Bryan?
Right.
Yes.
We had one high school, and I believe we only had two elementary schools at that time.
The elementary school was over on the west side of town, which was the old part of Bryan, and the other one was over here.
We had only one high school.
It was not anything like junior high, middle high and all, senior high and all that.
It was just high school.
Right.
And it was four years.
It was twelve, twelve grades then of school.
Twelve grades.
Right.
Okay.
Did, was it, were there very many in the school at, you know, when you went, where you were going or?
Well, not a great many.
I don't think we ever had more than thirty.
But you didn't have, you had, in other words, a teacher for each grade and so on too?
Yes.
For all the classes, right?
Did they, you also told me, or I know now that you are a librarian, how did you happen to choose this career?
It's just what I always wanted to do.
When I was 14 years old, I started working over in the old Carnegie Library building.
From that moment, I knew that's what I wanted to do.
Right.
Okay.
Could you relate a little bit of the history of the Bryan Library here, how it was established?
Yes.
When Bryan was first came into being, it was a pretty rough town.
It was completely
a town where an awful lot of people who didn't have any other place to go came.
Roughnecks, wanderers, people who'd been kicked out of other places.
There was actually a saloon on every corner.
Hangings and lynchings and shootings were the rule of the day.
But there also came into this community
number of very cultivated people who had come from the Old South.
They were people not only of wealth and influence, but people who knew what to do with it.
And prominent among these were some ladies who established what they called the Mutual Improvement Club.
This was in 1897.
The Mutual Improvement Club is now the most prestigious club in Bryan, which is the Bryan Women's Club.
And among these ladies were Mrs. Alastair Waldrop Sr., and Mrs. Rose Fountain Howell, and Mrs. George Brandon.
And these ladies felt that Brian needed a number of things.
There were over 4,000 people.
There were almost 5,000 people in Brazos County at that time.
And they decided that they were going to do something about the situation.
Well, they had several goals which they put down.
One of them was to get the cows off of Main Street.
And another was to have a park.
And the park, I may tell you, is this park right here where the library is at the moment.
And the third thing they wanted to do was to have a free public library.
And I may tell you in the beginning that in a very short while, just a matter of months, they had done all these things that they wanted to do.
They pretty quick got the cattle off of Main Street.
They took this piece of land and made it into a park, and they planted those oak trees.
No, I think the oak trees were planted later, sometime after World War I as a memorial to the men in Brazos County who had been killed in the war.
And then as for the library, these ladies, having their ears to the ground, heard that Andrew Carnegie was giving away millions of dollars
establish libraries.
This is really the most wonderful thing that ever happened for libraries in the United States.

So Mrs., I think it was Mrs. Brandon who had some connection with Andrew Carnegie, and they wrote to Mr. Carnegie and told him that they would like to have a library in Bryan, and they pointed out all the reasons why they needed a library in Bryan.

he wrote back immediately and said he would be pleased that was the word he used to give them a thousand dollars which they would use this money to build the building and that's what that building cost one thousand dollars under these terms that they the city would match this fund every year a thousand dollars to
buy books to run the library, pay personnel.
So the thing was accepted.
And an interesting thing is to go there and look at the minutes of the city council in those years.
And you find that many years they had to borrow money to keep their side of the bargain.
But they did.
So in 1903, on December the 14th, this library over here opened.
It was the biggest day in Bryan's history up to that point.
You can go back and read the Old Eagle and find out where everybody was on that day and what they were doing.
And if they were not attending the library opening, well, you knew exactly why they couldn't.
The way they got the books has always been interesting to me.
Miss Malcolm McInnis, who was one of my
high school teacher's father was on the faculty.
He was on the first faculty at A&M.
And he was also the first president of the library board, the old Carnegie building.
And he lived over in one of those gorgeous Victorian mansions over on 29th Street.
They tore it down now and made apartments out of it.
I'm sorry to say.
But he invited everybody in Brazos County to come to a party at his house.
But to come to the party, you had to bring a book.
So they all brought a book, and Miss Malcolm said that she remembers it.
She said it was just like heaven descending upon earth to have all those books.
And she used to sit for hours at the piano supposedly practicing, and all the while she had one of the books.
And she just lived in fear that she wouldn't get all the books read before they took them out of the house and put them in the library.
Well, over the years, of course, you know, the library's grown and grown and grown.
We do have some of those original books in the collection now.
You can go down and see that wonderful little handwriting on the cards that we still have.
Books are still there.
This library, I just arranged it so that when this library opened, I had it open on December the 14th.
That's great.
How long was the original building of the library here before it was reconstructed?
You mean the building over there?
Let's see, was the first library on this property here?
No, the first library was the old one over here that's still there.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
It's been there since 1903.
Since 1903.
And when was this building built here?
Well, let me see.
Maybe five, six years ago.
Five or six years ago.
OK. 1969, I believe, is when we opened, in December 1969.
OK.
You told me that you wanted to be a librarian.
Where did you get your schooling?
Well, I have a BA and an MA from the University of Texas at Austin, and I have an MS in Library Science from Louisiana State University.
Do you know approximately how many volumes they had here in the library when they started out as compared to today?
You mean the first library collection?
I think it was a thousand books.
Now we have 100,000.
That's great.
Of course, I guess the Depression hit here as much as it did anywhere else in the United States.
Could you describe how it affected your life or your lifestyle and maybe the people here in Vine?
Well, as I remember,
People here in Brown were not greatly affected by the Depression because their economy at that time depended upon the university.
Life went all about as usual.
Only thing I can remember about the Depression from my university days was that they kept having these
Saturdays when you could go to the movies free.
And we would all spend all day Saturday going to every movie house in Austin.
Free movies.
What changes in this community do you think have most affected its advancement and growth?
People all over the country are finding that this is an extremely pleasant place to live.
And there are just thousands of people who come into this community to live for no other reason than just that.
The life is about as leisurely as it can be in these days.
The people are kind, hospitable, and congenial.
And of course, it is a college town.
There's no getting away that I think for myself and for a lot of people that the pleasantest kind of place to live is a university town.
I've never lived in any other, so I don't really know how it would be.
Right.
What recollections do you have of Texas A&M University as it grew over the years?
Oh my.
Or just a view of them in a way that's interesting?

Well, from the time I first laid eyes on it, I remembered how it was, the university was founded, and it always amazed me to think that of all places in the world, now this is nothing but a little flat prairie out there.
that this should be the first land-grant college in the United States, which it is.
And it started out as with a few buildings, and Miss Malcolm told me also one time about how he had just married this beautiful, exquisite little dainty Mississippi belle and brought her to A&M.
The train was late, so
President Gathright had sent horse and buggy to pick them up and they got there, the train went there, so they went back.
So when they came to get off, he stepped down and then he held out his hand and let her step down and she put her lovely little foot right into a big mud hole.
And she lifted up her skirts and she looked around in amazement.
She couldn't see anything except miles and miles of prairie.
And she said, Major McInnes, where is the university?
What kinds of fads and fashions were popular when you were growing up?
Well, I can tell you that the main recreation for young people in this town was riding up and down Main Street.
There was nothing to do except go to the movies.
And it was onlywell, there were three movie houses.
Which ones were those?
Do you recall?
Oh, the Palace, the Queen, and the Dixie.
The Dixie was where they had westerns.
We had the second one that was at the Queen, and the first ones were at the Palace.
Were the roads paved in this town at that time?
Yes, but they had not always been.
Mrs. Donna Carnage was telling me about the first paved street they got in Bryan was Main Street, and she said that on that day, it was on a Saturday morning, and her brother
Walter Coulter.
They elected a queen of the paving, can you believe it?
A queen of the paving.
And that was Frances James, she became.
Karen's own of Jim Ferguson, and always went wherever he could to hear him, because he thought it was, of course, he knew as a renegade and all those things, but he was spectacular.
eloquent oratory was interesting.
Who exactly was Jim Ferguson?
Was he a mayor here?
No, no.
He was governor of Texas twice, and he was impeached.
He was, I guess, the only Texas governor who's ever been impeached.
I know he was.
So then he stepped right in and ran his wife for governor, and she used to call them all Ferguson, and she got elected.
What natural disasters that occurred in this area do you remember, and how did they affect the people in the landscape?
Well, there were several hurricanes.
One of them I remember after I came here to be director of this library, and I know that all the refugees that lived in the library during that time.
Oh, that was about 1969.
More like 59, I think.
Right.
Were there any floods back in the earlier days, like in the Browns River that occurred, you know, during your time?
Yes, long before my time, though.
What role has religion played in this community, and how has it changed over the years?
Every account that you read of the history of this area is that the churches and schools were in this town before the town was, right?
The oldest churches in town, the Episcopal Church, the Baptist Church, Methodist, Presbyterian, and the Catholic Church.
and the Christian Church.
I think those are the ones that were first here, and they were all established about the same time.
When was that approximately?
Okay.
And over the years, you know, we've got many churches now.
The Baptists have split into many, many sects.
Just all you have to do on Sunday morning is try to go to church yourself, to get through the parked cars to get to your own church.
Right.
Do you think there were more people at that timewell, I don't know, maybe that's not a question to answerthat were more involved in religion and religious activities, possibly, than there are today?
Yes, becausefor this reason.
Church was not only for church, but it was also for social.
In the early days, the only social life people had was in the church.
What kind of social activities were there?
Well, singing, sacred heart singing, socials, and what they used to call dinner on the ground, meeting all day, dinner on the ground.
In those that dance, there are some churches, you know, that dance, and others that don't, but dancing, the Episcopal Catholic Church for young people dances.
What technological changes do you think have had the greatest impact on this area?
I don't know, such as what?
Well, like, I don't know, it could be like, such as, I don't know, maybe farm machinery or the... Well, of course, farm machinery.
This is basically a ranching and...
plantation area and has always been, but machinery that had to do with any of those occupations would have a great impact upon us.
Most people, of course, I guess, were involved in agriculture during that time, right?
That's all there was to do.
Kids' stores.
Do you know what the main crops were that were grown in this area?
Cotton.
This is one of the biggest cotton planting areas in the world.
The Brazos Valley is supposed to be the richest, second maybe to Egypt.
Do you think agriculture is still as important to this area as it was?
Well, it's not as important as it was, but it's still certainly very important.
How do you feel thatthat Bryan or the community hashow has it most affected your life here?
I don't know exactly.
Let's see.
or what attributes maybe of this community do you feel are important to you?
I adore every inch of this town.
I would never live anywhere else.
You'd have to put me in jail to take me away from this town.
Could you tell me something a little bit about
the stores and the retail businesses here in town, some that were quite progressive or quite prominent here in Newtown?
Well, Waldrop's has always been here, just the Brown Brand store has just gone out of business.
They still have one at the college, and Eugene Edge on the corner is still here.
Conway is an old store.
Were theseare these department stores, or are these?
Waldrop's and Conway's are men's clothing stores, and Edge's is just that oldit's the only one in townjust an old-fashioned store where you can get everything, any way of clothing.
Okay.
Do you think that the growth of Bryan has had any negative aspects on the community?
No.
I think it's too big.
It makes me unhappy that I don't know where everybody lives.
You probably maybe have some friends or relatives that have lived here that have maybe moved out of this community.
Is there any particular reason or one maybe general reason they've moved?
from this area.
I think that the main reason people move from Bryan is that they find, they think they will be, it would be more advantageous to them, usually in the way of money, to go somewhere else.
I've never known but one person in all the years that I've lived in Bryan, that's a long time, who did not like it here, and who said so.
This was a person from the cold Middle West.
I see.
And I may say they have now gone back to the cold middle class.
But I've known many, many, many converted Yankees.
We love it.
Have, and I'm sure I guess a number of people have gone just because maybe the bigger towns have had more attraction?
Yes.
They, you know, in earlier days when the educational advantages weren't as great as they are here, they leave it other places to educate their children.
Okay.
Of course, let's see.
housing I'm sure in the earlier days was quite different than it is now.
They didn't use brick materials and so on to build houses.
How do you think, what were the styles like, you know, then as compared to today?
In architecture?
Well, the favorite kinds of architecture here were Greek Revival, which is plantation style, and Victorian.
We have several excellent examples of both of them.
Okay.
And they were, of course, the wooden frame, right?
Two-story, mostly, weren't they?
Yeah.
The Aston brothers, who came here from Alabama to plant cotton, built two gorgeous brick houses, one on the inside of town, one over on Texas Avenue burned 50 years ago.
And the other one is still, and it is a magnificent house.
It's just been bought by somebody with a large family, I'm happy to say.
It's over on the west side.
When were those built in this area?
Oh, long towards the turn of the century, after they had made their fortunes in cotton.
Okay.
Um, how do you, what do you feel is, uh,
about the impact of the railroad in this area, as far as the transportation.
Was it an important link to other towns and communities?
Well, there had never been Brown except for the railroad.
The railroad left Milliken and came to Brown, and that was when the town
came into existence.
Do you know when it, where was that?
Well, let's see.
It was in 1967.
Was it used a lot by the people here in Bryan to get to different communities everywhere?
Totally, yeah.
That was the only mode of transportation.
Right, yeah.
Okay.
You told me earlier there was a lot of renegades and saloons in this area.
what was when how long ago was that that was in the 1800s that was when in the earlier earlier days um
There have been, I believe, a lot of different ethnic backgrounds of peoples that have moved in the series.
Yes, very happily.
I always get this question, and I like to say I'm proud of the fact that this community has always been integrated.
This library has always been integrated.
When the problem of using the library came, you know, whether black people could use the library, they had always been using the library.
Had all the same privileges as anybody else.
The Mexican-Americans have been a great influence on this, you know, to have given it that leisurely, graceful, and colorful influence that only they could give.
We have a large bohemian
Were these different ethnic people, were they here when you were living here also?
Yes, they've always been here.
There's also a larger number of Italians in this community.
There's a large number of Italians.
What were the, what was the A&M University like when you were growing up?
Was there, of course, most, it was all male school at that time, and most, I guess all the men were in the corps, is that correct?
Yes.
Emphasis was definitely on the military.
Right.
And it was the most exciting place in the world for a girl to be.
That was the other occupation, I may tell you, of young people was for girls to get in cars and go out to A&M and
See the boys.
How didlet's seewere there any particularwell, let's see, whatI was trying to think.
You said that your father was at A&M.
Was your mother the housewife then, I guess, right?
My mother definitely objected to that terminology.
Oh, she did?
She was not a housewife.
Oh, okay.
